---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Icon from '../components/Icon.astro';


const X_URL = 'https://x.com/infiniteJX';
const LINKEDIN_URL = 'https://www.linkedin.com/in/judith-xia-a2321b1b2/';
const RECOMMEND_EMAIL = 'judithxia0314@gmail.com';
---

<Base
  title="Why this exists — Considered"
  description="Building products got easy. Finding the good ones got hard. Considered is a hand-picked collection of AI products made with care."
  locale="en"
  pagePath="/about/"
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <p class="product-cat">About</p>
    <h1>Why this exists<span class="full-stop">.</span></h1>
  </header>

  <div class="about-body">
    <p>
      In the last two years, AI made building software dramatically easier. Indie developers and
      weekend projects now ship real products in days. That part is wonderful. The side effect is
      not: dozens of AI products launch every day, and telling the carefully made ones from the
      hastily assembled ones has become genuinely hard work.
    </p>
    <p>
      The old discovery channels aren't much help. Launch platforms are gamed by vote pools and
      paid pushes. Social feeds are wall-to-wall promotion. And many AI products don't map to an
      obvious search keyword — you can't google your way to a tool you don't know exists. There's
      a saying that a product needs to cross your feed seven times before you'll try it. Good
      products get buried; users get numb.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile, the easier building gets, the scarcer taste becomes. Judgment — knowing what's
      actually good, and why — doesn't scale with the model releases.
    </p>
    <p>
      So this site runs in the opposite direction of the AI directory sites. Nothing here is
      auto-collected, nothing is ranked by algorithm, and no one can pay their way in. I try the
      products, keep the ones I find myself genuinely appreciating, and write down what makes
      each one special — less a review, more a note of gratitude to the people who sweat the
      details. If an entry hands you one tool that genuinely helps, it did its job.
    </p>
    <p>
      One more thing worth saying: absence isn't a verdict. If a product isn't here, it usually
      just means I haven't lived with it yet.
    </p>
    <p>
      The index is small on purpose, and it grows slowly. That's not a limitation. That's the
      product.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="about-block" id="editor">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span>The editor</span>
    </div>
    <div class="about-body">
      <p>
        I'm a product manager who builds AI products for a living — and can't stop trying
        everyone else's after hours. This site is where the keepers go. If you want to see the
        collection grow, or argue with a note, I'm around:
      </p>
      <p class="editor-links">
        <a class="rss-inline" href={X_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">X <Icon name="arrow-up-right" /></a>
        <a class="rss-inline" href={LINKEDIN_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn <Icon name="arrow-up-right" /></a>
        <a class="rss-inline" href="/rss.xml"><Icon name="rss" /> RSS</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-block" id="recommend">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span>Recommend a product</span>
    </div>
    <div class="about-body">
      <p>
        Found something made with care? I'd genuinely love to see it — several entries here
        started as someone's recommendation. Tell me what it is and what made you keep it:
        <a class="rss-inline" href={`mailto:${RECOMMEND_EMAIL}`}>{RECOMMEND_EMAIL}</a>.
        Recommendations are welcome; placement still isn't for sale.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
